	<Header validationStatus="Unknown" version="1.0" date="2026-07-15T00:00:00Z">
		<NoteSet>
			<Note>ST[13] Large Packet Transfer. See pus_analysis/pus13.md.</Note>
			<Note>Mission convention (Gap fix, see pus13.md Section c): the spec marks the "part" field
				as a "deduced size" octet-string for TM[13,3] and TC[13,11] (the last part), meaning the
				length is inferred from the surrounding CCSDS packet length. XTCE cannot express that
				directly for command arguments, and relying on an unverified "trailing binary consumes
				rest of packet" behaviour was flagged as risky in the analysis doc. Instead this mission
				fixes all non-last parts (TM[13,1]/[13,2], TC[13,9]/[13,10]) to a constant 64-byte
				part_data, and prefixes the last part (TM[13,3], TC[13,11]) with an explicit
				part_len:uint8 (1-64) followed by a part_data_last field whose size is dynamically
				derived from part_len (same validated pattern as yamcs-core's
				xtce/VariableBinary.xml test resource). This is genuinely variable-length (no
				zero-padding waste) and avoids the unverified XTCE feature entirely.</Note>
			<Note>Downlink trigger: the real ECSS spec never has ground command a ST[13] downlink -- it
				fires whenever some other on-board subsystem has a large TM to send. The simulator
				emulates this by periodically (every 20s) synthesizing a fake large payload on its own
				and downlinking it fragmented as TM[13,1]/[13,2]/[13,3], with no TC involved.</Note>
			<Note>Uplink reconstruction: the spec says the on-board software "reconstructs the large
				command and executes it" after TC[13,11], with no completion TM defined for success
				(only TM[13,16] on abort). This simulator treats the reassembled bytes as a raw embedded
				PUS TC packet (same idea as the ST[19]/ST[21] embedded-TC pattern) and dispatches it via
				the normal command path (PusSimulator.processTc), so the embedded command gets its own
				independent ACK/NACK/completion chain. The ground/test tooling is responsible for
				building a valid, CRC'd TC packet and splitting it into 64-byte chunks before uplinking
				it as TC[13,9]/[13,10]/[13,11].</Note>
			<Note>Only one uplink reassembly transaction is tracked at a time (mission simplification).
				A new TC[13,9] received while another transaction is still in progress aborts the old one
				(TM[13,16], InternalError) before starting the new one.</Note>
		</NoteSet>
	</Header>
